<br>
I believe that the &quot;In God we trust&quot; should be stricken from the bills because it is a lie.  If I am included in the &quot;we&quot; then it is not true that we all trust in god.  If I am not included than I have to wonder who gets to make the decision that I am not.<br>
<br>
The seperation of church and state is an idea that emerges from the first amendment.  It is not enumerated in the constitution but is found in a supreme court decision (Everson v Board) by Justice Black (usually a stark literalist) who wrote, <br>
<br>
&quot;The &quot;establishment of religion&quot; clause of the First Amendment means at least this: Neither a state nor the Federal Government can set up a church. Neither can pass laws which aid one religion, aid all religions, or prefer one religion over another. Neither can force nor influence a person to go to or to remain away from church against his will or <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> force him to profess a belief or disbelief in any religion</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. No person can be punished for entertaining or professing religious beliefs or disbeliefs, for church attendance or non-attendance. No tax in any amount, large or small, can be levied to support any religious activities or institutions, whatever they may be called, or whatever form they may adopt to teach or practice religion. Neither a state nor the Federal Government can, openly or secretly, participate in the affairs of any religious organizations or groups and vice versa. In the words of Jefferson, the clause against establishment of religion by law was intended to erect <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> &quot;a wall of separation between church and State.&quot;</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
It might not literally say it, but according to the Supreme Court that is what it means.  By creating an official time to say the pledge the state is forcing people to profess their belief or disbelief.<br>
<br>
Linking to Mcarthyism is not far fetched in the least.  'Under God' was added to fight against atheist-communism and nothing more.  <br>
<br>
To say that it isn't coercive is to say that there is no peer pressure.  I got in many arguments with people when I refused to stand for the pledge or say 'Under God.'  Most people just assume you're a stupid little punk or rebel and don't understand the insult it is.  Imagine being the lone child in a class who does not believe in God and feeling suddenly out of place with society.<br>
<br>
Removing 'Under God' is not forcing my views on anyone else.  I'm not making you say, &quot;one nation, under absolutely no creator, ...&quot; I'm advocating for state neutrality in the issue where they make no assumptions of religious matters, not that they assume that there is nothing.  It is the Judeo-Christian belief that is pushed upon people by knowing that congress officially assumes a creator which is preposterous imho.  <br>
<br>
Schools can and should teach tolerance and good citizenship, but must not favor one religion over another or belief over non-belief. To do otherwise would, in the words of Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O’Connor, “send a message to nonadherents that they are outsiders, not full members of the …community.” <br>
<br>
Varro <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/udelthanorsilverthorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Delthanor Silverthorn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Guk Knight</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(6/27/02 5:15:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=361.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: STOOPID..</span><hr size=1> While personally I am all in favor of leaving &quot;under God&quot; in the pledge, as it conforms to my personal beliefs, the court does have good reason to make this judgement. When deciding on the constitutional nature of a law, the court will look into WHY the law was made. <br>
<br>
Congressman Louis C. Rabaut from Michigan was the House sponsor of the bill which added “under God” to our Pledge. Rabaut testified before a congressional committee in support of the legislation. He said <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
 “the children of our land, in the daily recitation of the pledge in school, will be daily impressed with a true understanding of our way of life and its origins.” <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The President of the United States in 1954 was Dwight Eisenhower, who said when he signed the legislation <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
 “From this day forward, the millions of our school children will daily proclaim in every city and town, every village and rural schoolhouse, the dedication of our nation and our people to the Almighty.”<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
From this, it seems that they knowingly were inserting words to inject into schools a belief in God. This can be construed as Congress passing a law to endorse a religious point of view.  While in this case it happens to coincide with my beliefs, I'm certain that another case in the future could contradict my beliefs.  <br>
<br>
We do have to be wary of indoctrination by our government schools, but honestly, this &quot;under God&quot; phrase is probably the smallest worry in a long list of things that bother me about what's taught in our schools these days.  The current government school agenda appears to want the next generation to be disrespectful of our founding fathers and their beliefs, those who have died to protect us and our liberties, and too dumb to know better. <br>
<br>
What our founding fathers achieved is an amazing document and system that was greater then themselves. Our nation was founded with radical ideas, about freedom, liberty, self-determination, and economy. They took some of the best ideas about government from history, wrapped them up and put them to work. Our founding fathers were extremists, because extremeists make dreams become reality.  They were also for the most part Christians of one flavor or another.  That CANNOT be discounted when appraising what they created, because to allow freedom is a radical belief built upon by faith in God and man.<br>
<br>
From what our kids seem to be taught these days, our founding fathers were a bunch of bigoted slave owning scumbags, and today's America is oppressive, isolationist, domineering, imperialist, weak, corrupt, and warmongering zealots. Or so they say.  <br>
<br>
The arguement made by the man behind the court case (I heard him on the radio today) is that so much evil has been done in the world due to and in the name of religion, so he feels religion should be stricken from the Pledge.  He totally fails to realize that evil is evil, and is not tied to religion, any more than massive fires are tied to Mrs. O'Leary's cow.  Yes, it does happen, but Stalin and Mao were anti-religion (more accuratly, pushed a religion of The State) and killed a combined 50+ million people.  He also seems to miss that Athiesm is a belief system too.  <br>
<br>
In a way I feel sorry for him, because he seems to have missed that it's not religion in these cases that was bad, it was Power.  Powerful men in powerful positions who abused that power.  Torquemada, Bin Laden, Stalin, Mao, Jim Jones, and many others have committed terrible acts, not due to their professed belief systems, but due to the corruption of power.  By being able to kill or imprison a man with a word.  Being able to enforce their convenience on others.  <br>
<br>
And in this case, isn't what this man is trying to do to the country?  <br>
<br>
And the constitution is not only there to protect the minority from the majority (it doesn't do that all that well) it's there to protect the majority from the minority.  (See South Africa:Apartheid)<br>
<br>
Bah, I'm rambling. Must be my old age. <p><img border=0 src="http://users.rcn.com/cooley2/Delthanorsig.jpg"><BR>
