<br>
That's part of it, but even moreso because, as I stated previously, the pledge of allegiance is an oath of loyalty.  If your convictions or beliefs preclude you from reciting such an oath then you shouldn't do so.<br>
<br>
and  &quot;I don't it must mean that I'm not a ‘true’ American.”<br>
<br>
Well, since you want to try an extremist method as justification of trying to erase the fact that a belief in God is what inspired the establishment of this country (Revisionist history), unless you are a Native American then no, you are NOT a true American.  If you are, then you might have a legitimate claim of disenfranchisement as an American by the U. S government in my eyes.  If you embrace the concept that Americans are anyone who accepts and defends the ideals of freedom and basic liberty for all regardless of race, nationality, or religious beliefs, why do you care what others believe?  The pledge is an oath of loyalty to those ideals not a demand for you to renounce your beliefs simply because of a reference to a deity.  You're not even asked to swear that loyalty by said god, unlike swearing an oath to tell the truth in court.<br>
<br>
&quot;BTW, read up on some Jefferson before you attribute Christianity to all the founders, Jefferson was quite a deist in many ways.&quot;<br>
<br>
At no point did I attribute Christianity as the practicing religion of all the founders.  Acknowledgment of the existence of the Christian god does not make one a Christian.  Secondly, Thomas Jefferson was a Freemason and many of their basic ideas are similar to deism (Another philosophy/religion that acknowledges the existence of a god.)  While Freemasonry does not espouse one god over another, (They only require you to believe in one central divine being.  Usually generically referred to as the Creator or the Architect.) they claim their origins trace back to a sect of Judaism that arose at the time of King Soloman's reign.  Sounds to me like he was a believer in a single god.<br>
<br>
Varro states:  &quot;Now that is one big stupid stupid stupid statement. It appears you don't understand the difference between espousing the existence of a god and asserting that some people believe in and are motivated by God.&quot;<br>
<br>
No basis of fact?  Is my assertion that a push for removal for books of any sort of &quot;religious&quot; theme be called for removal really so stupid?  Take a look at the rise of different empires/regimes in history.  People with agendas to fulfill always attack some national or cultural symbol first.  Then it's on to books with different ideas, then intellectuals/scientists who support borderline, unpopular, or opposing views.  It's a gradual progression.  They aren't going to target the mundane everyday items (like money) that everyone sees on a daily basis until their ideas have become entrenched in the minds of the average majority.  <br>
<br>
Books are banned in communities across the U. S. for usage of words like &quot;nigger&quot;, references to witchcraft (A religious practice that sometimes espouses the belief of a higher power), even expressing an unorthodox view of some of the different mainstream religions in the world today.  You have people swearing up and down that events like the Holocaust didn't happen or that the moon landing was faked and they're taken seriously.  Delthanor and I can't possibly be the only people who are noticing this current trend of vilifying of this nation's founders as justification to try and eliminate and all references to its foundation.<br>
<br>
Varro states:  &quot;Most people just assume you're a stupid little punk or rebel and don't understand the insult it is.&quot;<br>
<br>
Most kids refusing to recite the pledge were stupid little punks simply trying to get a rise out of their teacher and disrupt the class.  However, where I lived, refusing to say the pledge quickly got old when Jehovah's Witnesses started attending the school and they refused to recite the pledge for religious reasons. The one I knew stated she didn't recite it because they didn't believe in swearing any form of oath to anyone other than God.  At least she has a legitimate reason why as opposed to &quot;Nyah, nyah you can't make me say it so I'm not gonna say it.&quot;  And it wasn't really a big deal.<br>
<br>
Varro states:  &quot;This is an argument with no basis and is just to inspire a fear of religious persecution by an atheist minority when the truth is that atheism is much more likely to be persecuted.&quot;<br>
<br>
and  <br>
<br>
&quot;Imagine being the lone child in a class who does not believe in God and feeling suddenly out of place with society.&quot;<br>
<br>
Historically, it's people who have taken a stand on supporting their religion who have been persecuted and/or murdered for it, not people denying the existence thereof.  If are you implying that atheists don't try to push their beliefs on others, insult, or persecute those who do believe in a god then I'm going to have to tell you from personal direct experience that you're dead wrong.  I've been singled and called a stupid fool in front of the entire class for believing in a god by a professed atheist teacher.  Anyone who has the courage to stand up for their convictions is going to find themselves shunned when it goes against the status quo.  That's a fact of life.  Deal with it and move on.<br>
<br>
Gaelron states:  &quot;If you were raised without religion would you believe in the same way?&quot;<br>
<br>
I can't answer that accurately.  My experiences involving religion have influenced my beliefs.  Just as my parents were influenced by religion as they grew up.  I think the only person who could probably answer that most accurately would be someone who was raised atheist, but even then I think that religion would have impacted their experiences and beliefs.<br>
<br>
