<br>
<br>
Millikin, thanks for being 100x the arguer Drevis is<br>
<br>
My point with the book issue is not that I doubt the possibility of books being banned, but that I believe that issue is seperate from the one we are talking about.  It is a what if claim that really has no basis in this argument because the reasons for banning a book are quite different from the reasons for removing &quot;Under God&quot; from the pledge.  Removing under god is to ensure the impartial nature of state authority when referring to religion.  God has a place in school, but it would be in a comparative religion course, or history, etc... not in a pledge.<br>
<br>
Also, I'm not suggesting that atheists don't attack religious beliefs on a personal level, but that is protected speech, just as it is the right of a guy at my uni to carry around a sign saying that I as an atheist am a disgusting creature to him.  I respect people of faith and I'm glad this topic hasn't degenerated into a pro/anti Christianity thread.  If your teacher ridiculed you for your beliefs you have the right to protest and some would argue the responsibility to do so, so he doesn't ridicule any other people of faith.<br>
<br>
People of faith have historically been oppressed, I agree with that completely, but I must argue that they were oppressed by people of a different faith in most cases.  The issue is more related to the beliefs of the majority or elite vs the beliefs of the powerless.  As you said, it is a battle against the status quo.  <br>
<br>
I believe in the constitution.  There is a school of thought that true patriotism is criticizing and evaluating the government to keep them true to the ideals this country was founded upon.  For those who want to argue that we aren't following the intent of the framers I ask what do you know about the original interpretation of our bill of rights.  For a while people thought freedom of speech just meant you couldn't be arrested prior to writing offensive material, but you could be afterward.  Search and siezure rules were unenforcable because if evidence was taken without a warrant it could still be used in court.  How about seperate but equal, dread scott, and other cases involving civil rights.  The Supreme Court is given the authority to rule on the meaning of the constitution for a reason.  Times change and ideals change.  The founding fathers are at a disadvantage of 200+ years.<br>
<br>
How the majority can misconstrue this as the tyranny of a minority group is beyond me.  In those western states affected by this ruling you as an individual can still say the pledge of allegiance until your tongue goes numb.  At my old highschool students used to pray around the flag pole every morning.  These are perfectly fine to me and I salute those who wish to express their beliefs.  The only thing that changes is that you can not set aside spacific class time to say the pledge because that is government endorcement of religion, if not a specific religion, then at least the existence of a higher power.  That government endorcement is what is wrong, not the expression of belief.<br>
<br>
