<br>
the issue here is one of the constitutionality of the act that added the words &quot;under God&quot; to the pledge of allegiance.  as we saw from the quote from President Eisenhower: &quot;From this day forward, the millions of our school children will daily proclaim in every city and town, every village and rural schoolhouse, the dedication of our nation and our people to the Almighty,&quot; the motives behind its inclusion were questionable at best from a constitutional standpoint.  It was a political move by vote-coddling republicans that passed this act, and it is a political move of today's politicians to slam the new ruling without ever addressing the actual issue.  President Bush, our leading politician, showed his typical capacity for understanding the complexeties of an issue by simply calling the ruling &quot;ridiculous.&quot;<br>
<br>
the ruling was not ridiculous.  it was unpopular.  the ability to look past the surface at the details of an issue, and to go against the popular opinion if need be, is something our populace seems to be sadly lacking in.  it is the responsibility of each American citizen to exercise their powers of discernment, to think before they speak, and to constantly examine their thought processes.  differences of opinion will always exist, as they must in a democracy, and if those opinions are all educated and well expressed, our nation will be continue to be refined and bettered.  if the opinions of the masses are not educated, but are based rather on fear, dogma, superstition, or simple hive-mind syndrome, then our fragile democratic republic is in grave danger.<br>
<br>
this is what scares me the most about this entire episode; there has been so little difference of public opinion, so few people willing to look logically at the facts of the case.  everyone hears their leaders denouncing the ruling as ridiculous, and their opinions follow suite directly.  i'll admit this case is an easy target for the politicians to build popularity be denouncing it.  attacking an institution like the pledge of allegiance, at a time when feelings of nationalism and love of tradition are very high in our country, was unwise at best.  the timing was poor, and it is indeed of somewhat trivial importance compared to the other problems our nation is facing.  still, the band wagon jumping, hive mind mentality that i see happening here is truly frightening.<br>
<br>
Millikin, i challenge your assertion that our country was founded solely upon a belief in God: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Well, since you want to try an extremist method as justification of trying to erase the fact that a belief in God is what inspired the establishment of this country (Revisionist history), unless you are a Native American then no, you are NOT a true American<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->.  many of our our ancestors came to this land from european nations who had a strong state-sponsored belief in God.  the new nation was founded in large part by persons believing in God, but it was not founded <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> on that belief</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  it was founded, rather, on a belief in freedom, an idea which was indeed radical in the european countries that harbored a strong belief in God.  this concept of freedom transcended in importance specific religious beliefs, and from it a country eventually emerged that is now a haven for free speech, freedom of thought, and freedom of religion.  it would be a terrible mistake to give away any of these aspects of our republic to satiate any party, be it the minority or majority.  <br>
<br>
is a belief in God too closely incorporated in our government?  i'm not going to debate that here, but i will say that it is a subject deserving of the attention and honest assessment of all american citizens.  to so readily dismiss it shows a mental lethargy and an unhealthy dependence on the consensus to form our opinions on important matters of state.  a democracy comprised of individuals such as this can not stand long.  please, think before you form your opinions, it is your responsibility to your nation.<br>
