Bubba <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/ubulvaihammersson.showPublicProfile?language=EN>BulvaiHammersson</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Dar Knight</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(6/28/02 8:03:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=361.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Under God and proud of it.</span><hr size=1> This has been an amazing. After seeing all sort of useless and idiotic drivel in other OT threads, I expected this one to sound off witht he same brand of muddle-headed chest-pounding. I am pleased to say that, for the most part, it hasn't.<br>
<br>
1) By _strict_ interpretation of the Establishment Clause (this whole seperation of Church and State thing), the phrase &quot;Under God&quot; in our Pledge is very much Unconstitutional. I say this because of the intent behind the addition of the phrase in 54 (I think). The intent, as others have covered, was to actively promote religion in the face of &quot;Godless Communism&quot;. Nuff said about the phrase's Unconstitutionality.<br>
<br>
2) The court's decision was not bone-headed, it was right. What was boneheded was the lawsuit. The jerk-off bringing suit is a rampant publicity hound. Look at his history of Mikey vs The US Govt type lawsuits on damned near everything even vaguely related to the Establishment clause. What a pud. It is my hope that his daughter grows up and rewards this man's callous manipulation of his own child with a great &quot;Mommy Dearest&quot; type book. He deserves it for this act, IMO.<br>
<br>
3) Any time &quot;God&quot; is brought up, people do tend to get overly excited. This is because many people are inherently and horribly insecure about their beliefs. Do you know which group gets the most excited and voluable, and thus looks the most insecure? The atheists. It has been a long time since atheists were actively persecuted for their lack of beliefs. It has been mere minutes since the last time an atheist persecuted a Christian for their state of Belief.<br>
<br>
4) To quote Varro, &quot;I don't see why your personal religious beliefs have to become part of doctrine from a body that represents the total population, especially given that the seperation of church and state demands that the authority be seperated from religion,&quot;. Interesting thought, Varro, considering you are espousing the use of that self-same authority to enforce your lack of religious beliefs on everyone else. Atheism, though it is a thoroughly bankrupt non-philosophy, has become a religion just like any other. It is simply less organized. Atheists use different terminology for their actions, but anyone with a bit of intelligence can look at atheism and see Missionary Work, Spreading the Word of No-God, etc. Give it up. Admit it. Atheism is a religion.<br>
<br>
5) Whenever this sort of argument comes up, people, again like Varro, love to bring up wonderfully poetic quotes about the Tyranny of the Majority. Yessiree, our nation is a Republic precisely to prevent the tyranny of the Majority. The problem here is that crap lawsuits like this swing the pendulum the other way. We have been victims of something far worse in the latter half of the XXth century and the start of the XXIst century - the Tyranny of the &quot;Oppressed&quot; Minority. How, precisely, do you rate? Do you pay that much in taxes? Do you support the pillars of society SO much that your every whim must be catared to? Are your sensibilities so delicate that you simply cannot abide by something so trivial? Yes, the phrase is Unconstitutional and should be struck, but why does this give you, the atheist, any right to &quot;pound the podium&quot; or &quot;preach from the pulpit&quot; as you accuse the Religious Right of doing. <br>
<br>
I am not one for Moral Relativism in the slightest, but this is one of thoce cases where the &quot;oppressed&quot; party is no better in the slightest than the &quot;oppressing&quot; party. They rail against the vile majority &quot;forcing&quot; majority beliefs on them, and thus seek, like Nietzche's Priest, to supplant Majority beliefs with their own Minority beliefs and then require the govt to enforce them in equally oppressive fashion. History will generally show that the laws tend to become even more restrictive after such a cry for &quot;freedom&quot; from &quot;oppression&quot; is heard.<br>
<br>
The bottom line here is that we have become a society which caters desperately to anyone with enough of a lack of self-esteem to claim &quot;victim&quot; status. This Nudrow (sp?) wacko has finally found himself a path by which to assault the Right/Conservative side. He sought to assault it via various lawsuits before, none of which got anywhere. Thus he chooses something so intransically American as the Pledge to assault and finally gets the attention he so desperately craves. Pathetic. Equally pathetic as the craven minority &quot;victims&quot; that seek to become the Oppressors.<br>
<br>
So, in all, the decision was right, the motivation was wrong. <p>a_Bearhat01<BR>
